    <div class="headline-container plain">
        <h1>Congestion Charge operational from Friday 2 January after festive period suspension</h1>
        <div class="content-page-press-release">
        29 December 2008
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="main-and-aside r">
    <div class="main" role="main">

    <div class="article-teaser">
        Transport for London (TfL) is reminding motorists that the Congestion Charge will be operational from Friday 2 January 2009, after the festive period suspension.
        
    </div>



 <div class="on-this-page">
<p>For the fifth year running, motorists do not have to pay the Congestion Charge from Thursday 25 December until Thursday 1 January inclusive, when traffic levels are lighter.</p>
<p>Graeme Craig, TfL's Director of Congestion Charging and Traffic Enforcement, said: 'The Congestion Charge will operate as usual from 2 January so, while the start of this week remains charge-free, motorists will need to pay the charge to drive within the zone on Friday.' 
<hr>
<br><strong>Notes to editors: </strong>
<p>
<ul type="circle">
<li>The Congestion Charge is an &pound;8 daily charge for driving a vehicle within the Congestion Charging zone between 7.00am and 6.00pm, Monday to Friday </li>
<li>There are a number of different payment methods for paying the Congestion Charge including:</li></ul>
<blockquote>
<li><a title="CCLondon website" href="http://www.cclondon.com/">online</a> </li>
<li>by calling 0845 900 1234 </li>
<li>by text message </li>
<li>at selected retail outlets and petrol stations </li>
<li>by post </li>
<li>at a self-service machine</li></blockquote>
<p>
<ul type="circle">
<li><a title="Congestion charging" href="http://www.tfl.gov.uk/roadusers/congestioncharging/default.aspx">Read more about Congestion Charging</a></li></ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>

     

        
        
        
